---
import Layout from "../../layouts/Layout.astro";
import LessonShell from "../../components/LessonShell.astro";
import Reveal from "../../components/Reveal.astro";
import { LESSONS } from "../../data/curriculum";

const lesson = LESSONS.find((l) => l.id === "agents-setup")!;
---

<Layout title={`${lesson.title} · Learn Claude`}>
  <main>
    <LessonShell lesson={lesson}>
      <p>
        Time to set one up for real. We'll install <strong>Hermes Agent</strong> by Nous Research —
        a background daemon that gives Claude persistent memory across sessions, schedules tasks,
        and can respond on Telegram or Discord. The pattern is the same for most other agents in this category.
      </p>

      <div class="callout">
        <strong>Two install paths.</strong> Pick whichever fits.<br/>
        <strong>A. As a Claude Code plugin</strong> — easiest if you already have Claude Code working (lesson <a href="/lessons/code-install">2.2</a>).<br/>
        <strong>B. Standalone</strong> — one curl command, runs on its own.
      </div>

      <h2>Path A · Claude Code plugin (recommended)</h2>
      <ol class="steps">
        <li>Open Claude Code in any project folder: <code class="inline">claude</code></li>
        <li>Add the Hermes plugin marketplace:
          <pre style="background: var(--surface-2); padding: 0.6rem 0.85rem; border-radius: 8px; font-family: var(--mono); font-size: 0.85rem; margin: 0.4rem 0;">/plugin marketplace add sypsyp97/claude-hermes</pre>
        </li>
        <li>Install:
          <pre style="background: var(--surface-2); padding: 0.6rem 0.85rem; border-radius: 8px; font-family: var(--mono); font-size: 0.85rem; margin: 0.4rem 0;">/plugin install claude-hermes@claude-hermes</pre>
        </li>
        <li>Start the daemon and walk through the setup wizard:
          <pre style="background: var(--surface-2); padding: 0.6rem 0.85rem; border-radius: 8px; font-family: var(--mono); font-size: 0.85rem; margin: 0.4rem 0;">/claude-hermes:start</pre>
          <p>The wizard asks about: model, heartbeat interval, Telegram/Discord bots (optional), security pin. Hermes uses Claude Code's existing credentials, so no separate API key needed for this path.</p>
        </li>
        <li>That's it. Hermes is now running in the background. Try sending it a task from within Claude Code, or message your Telegram/Discord bot if you set one up.</li>
      </ol>

      <h2>Path B · Standalone install</h2>
      <p>On Linux, macOS, or WSL2:</p>
      <pre style="background: #1c1916; color: #e8dec8; padding: 1rem; border-radius: 12px; font-family: var(--mono); font-size: 0.85rem; line-height: 1.5;">curl -fsSL https://raw.githubusercontent.com/NousResearch/hermes-agent/main/scripts/install.sh | bash</pre>
      <p>The installer offers to install <strong>Bun</strong> (the only runtime dependency) if it's missing.</p>

      <p>Then set up your API key:</p>
      <pre style="background: #1c1916; color: #e8dec8; padding: 1rem; border-radius: 12px; font-family: var(--mono); font-size: 0.85rem;">echo "ANTHROPIC_API_KEY=sk-ant-…" &gt;&gt; ~/.hermes/.env</pre>

      <p>Pick a model:</p>
      <pre style="background: #1c1916; color: #e8dec8; padding: 1rem; border-radius: 12px; font-family: var(--mono); font-size: 0.85rem;">hermes model      # interactive picker
# or
hermes chat --provider anthropic --model claude-sonnet-4-6</pre>

      <h2>Verifying it works</h2>
      <ol class="steps">
        <li>Send Hermes a one-line task: <em>"Summarize what's in ~/Documents and propose three folders to organize it."</em></li>
        <li>Watch it pick up the task. It will read files (asking for approval where needed) and write a plan.</li>
        <li>Close your terminal. Come back later. Hermes is still running. <strong>The memory persisted.</strong></li>
      </ol>

      <h2>What's different from Claude Code</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Persistent.</strong> Claude Code is per-session. Hermes lives in the background and remembers.</li>
        <li><strong>Scheduled.</strong> "Every Monday at 9, scan my inbox and draft three follow-up emails."</li>
        <li><strong>Multi-channel.</strong> Speak to it via your terminal, Telegram, Discord, or voice transcription.</li>
        <li><strong>Skill-learning.</strong> Hermes turns recurring tasks into <em>reusable skills</em> automatically.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>What about OpenClaw?</h2>
      <p>Same shape, different defaults. If you want a runtime that coordinates multiple coding CLIs as one (Claude Code + Codex + Cursor Agent under one orchestrator), OpenClaw is the route. Setup boils down to:</p>
      <pre style="background: var(--surface-2); padding: 0.6rem 0.85rem; border-radius: 8px; font-family: var(--mono); font-size: 0.85rem;">npm install -g openclaw      # or the install script from the docs
openclaw init
export ANTHROPIC_API_KEY=sk-ant-…
openclaw run</pre>
      <p>See <a href="https://docs.openclaw.ai" target="_blank" rel="noopener">docs.openclaw.ai</a> for the current install command — the project moves fast.</p>

      <h2>Safety hygiene for any agent</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Run with a budget.</strong> Set a spend cap on your Anthropic account.</li>
        <li><strong>Sandbox the workspace.</strong> Give the agent its own folder, not your home directory, on the first run.</li>
        <li><strong>Read the diffs.</strong> Especially during the first week — make sure the agent's idea of "improve this" matches yours.</li>
        <li><strong>Rotate the key</strong> if you ever paste it somewhere it shouldn't be.</li>
      </ul>

      <div class="tip">
        <strong>Next.</strong> The <a href="/lessons/ship-it">capstone lesson</a> walks through three real tools you can build today —
        you can do them in Claude.ai (no install) or extend them into a Hermes/OpenClaw setup once you're comfortable.
      </div>

      <Reveal q="What if I get stuck during install?">
        Paste the error into Claude Code or claude.ai. The model is good at diagnosing setup issues, especially common Node/npm/Python path problems.
      </Reveal>
      <Reveal q="Can I use these with a local model instead of Claude?">
        Most can. Hermes, OpenClaw, aider, and OpenHands all support Ollama (local) and OpenRouter (proxy). You give up some capability but gain privacy.
      </Reveal>
    </LessonShell>
  </main>
</Layout>
